result.execSummary:
The defendant Jonvanta Cortez White was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Armed Robbery with Threat of Force [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Signed Earned Release Program/Substance Abuse Program Order mailed to DOC-Warden Jeffrey Pugh, 2909 E. Park Avenue, Chippewa Falls, WI 54729.

Order amending judgment of conviction; signed by Judge Donald for Judge Colon and filed.
Pursuant to Sec 973.01, WI Stats. JONVANTA WHITE (DOB. 02-07-1988) was sentenced to a bifurcated sentence of 3 years confinement and 4 years extended supervision for a total of 7 years.
Pursuant to Sec. 302.05(3)(c), WI Stats., within 30 days after the court has been notified that the defendant has successfully completed the Earned Release Program, the court shall modify the bifurcated sentence.  The portion of the Confinement Time not served will be added to the Extended Supervision portion of the sentence.  The total length of the sentence will not change.
Whereas, JONVANTA WHITE (DOB. 02-07-1988) entered and began participation in the Earned Release Program on 03-28-2016.
Whereas, JONVANTA WHITE (DOB. 02-07-1988) has successfully completed the Earned Release Program of 08-12-2016.
It is ordered that the Department of Corrections will effectuate the change from Confinement to Extended Supervision upon receipt of this order, determining the actual number of days served in Confinement and changing the remaining Confinement to Extended Supervision.  The number of days that are converted from Confinement Time to Extended Supervision will be determined by DOC Central Records, and will be based upon actual release date.
It is further ordered that the Warden/Superintendent of the institution to which the prisoner is assigned shall effect his or her release upon receipt of this order.
In all other respects, the original judgment herein is affirmed.
Paperwork forwarded to the Clerk of Court's Office to amend the judgment of conviction.
DOC is requesting the Court to authorize the inmate's release and conversion of remaining confinement time to extended supervision.  Assigned to Br. 18 Judge Colon. os

Certification of SENTENCING HEARING transcript commencing OCTOBER 3, 2014, received and filed. (21 Pages.)
Copy of transcript forwarded to:  INSTITUTION.  jm

Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in court with attorney Daryl A. Kastenson.  Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in custody.  James W. Frisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Parties have reached an agreement.
Upon stipulation of the parties, Court ordered restitution set at $1,700.00 payable to the victim, Teri H.  The Court ordered that restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.
with attached Restitution Worksheet filed by ADA James Frisch on behalf of the State.

Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in court with attorney Daryl A. Kastenson.  Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in custody.  James W. Frisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeds. Statements made by the State, defense and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 7 YEARS.  
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 3 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 4 YEARS.
Credit for 162 days time served.

Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Court finds defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION (AS TO COUNT 1):
* Comply with the standard rules of extended supervision.
* No contact with the victims; Dejevon C., Teri H., and Kevin B.
* Complete a job training program to enhance ability to obtain employment.
* Obtain a GED or HSED.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample (unless previously done) and PAY DNA surcharge.  The Court ordered that the DNA surcharge be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges. The Court ordered that the court costs, fees, and surcharges be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Restitution to be determined at a Restitution Hearing.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in court with attorney Daryl A. Kastenson.  Defendant Jonvanta Cortez White in custody.  James W. Frisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms or body armor. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
